.\" b76pipe(3) — Base76 7‑bit binary pipeline encoder/decoder
.\"
.Dd April 15, 2026
.Dt B76PIPE 3
.Os
.Sh NAME
.Nm b76pipe
.Nd reversible Base76 7‑bit binary pipeline encoder/decoder
.Sh SYNOPSIS
.Nm
.Op Fl r
.Op Fl i Ar infile
.Op Fl o Ar outfile
.Op Ar message
.Sh DESCRIPTION
The
.Nm
utility implements a reversible Base76 transformation pipeline using the
canonical Willtech Base76 tools:
.Pp
.Bl -bullet -compact
.It
dec2base76.py
.It
base76todec.py
.It
hex2base76.py
.It
base76tohex.py
.It
base76_alphabet.py
.El
.Pp
No Base76 logic is reimplemented in the shell script; all encoding and decoding
is delegated to the Python tools listed above.
.Pp
The pipeline transforms an ASCII message into a layered Base76 representation
passing through a 7‑bit binary stage, and can reconstruct the original message
when invoked with the
.Fl r
flag.

.Sh FORWARD PIPELINE
The forward transformation consists of the following stages:
.Bl -enum
.It
ASCII input is converted to hexadecimal and encoded into Base76 using
.Pa hex2base76.py .
This produces the canonical Base76 string
.Em B1 .
.It
Each character of
.Em B1
is decoded to its integer index (0–75) using
.Pa base76todec.py .
Each index is rendered as a 7‑bit binary value.
.It
All 7‑bit values are concatenated into a single binary stream and converted into
literal ASCII characters '0' and '1'.
.It
Each ASCII '0' and '1' is mapped to its ASCII code (48 and 49 respectively).
These decimal values are encoded using
.Pa dec2base76.py .
The concatenation of these Base76 encodings forms the final output.
.El

.Sh REVERSE PIPELINE
The reverse transformation reconstructs the original message:
.Bl -enum
.It
Each Base76 character in the encoded message is decoded to a decimal value using
.Pa base76todec.py .
Valid values are 48 (ASCII '0') and 49 (ASCII '1').
.It
The recovered ASCII '0'/'1' characters form a binary stream, which is split into
7‑bit groups.
.It
Each 7‑bit group is converted to a decimal index (0–75) and encoded back into a
Base76 character using
.Pa dec2base76.py ,
reconstructing the original Base76 string
.Em B1 .
.It
.Em B1
is decoded back to hexadecimal using
.Pa base76tohex.py
and converted to ASCII, yielding the original message.
.El

.Sh OPTIONS
.Bl -tag -width Ds
.It Fl r
Reverse mode. Decode an encoded Base76 bitstream back to the original ASCII
message.
.It Fl i Ar infile
Read input from
.Ar infile
instead of the command line.
.It Fl o Ar outfile
Write output to
.Ar outfile
instead of standard output.
.El

.Sh EXIT STATUS
.Bl -tag -width Ds
.It 0
Success.
.It >0
An error occurred, such as invalid Base76 input, malformed bitstream, or I/O
failure.
.El

.Sh EXAMPLES
Encode a message:
.Pp
.Dl $ b76pipe "Hello world"
.Pp
Decode a message:
.Pp
.Dl $ b76pipe -r "BASE76_ENCODED_DATA"
.Pp
Encode from a file:
.Pp
.Dl $ b76pipe -i input.txt -o encoded.txt
.Pp
Decode from a file:
.Pp
.Dl $ b76pipe -r -i encoded.txt -o decoded.txt

.Sh IMPLEMENTATION NOTES
The script is written for OpenBSD
.Pa /bin/ksh
(pdksh) and avoids non‑portable constructs such as
.Dq for (( ... ))
and substring slicing. All loops use
.Xr cut 1
and
.Xr bc 1
for compatibility.

